
<h1>Common Daily Medicines for Individuals Over 65</h1>

<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Aspirin</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Aspirin is often prescribed for its blood-thinning properties, reducing the risk of heart
            attacks and strokes in older adults.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Statins (e.g., Atorvastatin)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Statins help lower cholesterol levels, reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Calcium Supplements</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Calcium is crucial for bone health, and supplements may be recommended to prevent
            osteoporosis in seniors.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Vitamin D Supplements</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Often prescribed to seniors for bone health and to prevent vitamin D deficiency.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Metformin</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Commonly prescribed for managing type 2 diabetes in older adults.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Anti-hypertensives (e.g., Lisinopril)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Medications to control high blood pressure and reduce the risk of cardiovascular
            events.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Thyroid Medications (e.g., Levothyroxine)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Prescribed for individuals with hypothyroidism to regulate thyroid hormone levels.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Folic Acid</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Often recommended for seniors to support heart health and prevent anemia.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Anticoagulants (e.g., Warfarin)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Blood thinners prescribed to prevent blood clots and reduce the risk of stroke.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Antiplatelet Medications (e.g., Clopidogrel)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Helps prevent blood clots and is commonly prescribed for heart conditions.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Proton Pump Inhibitors (e.g., Omeprazole)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Reduces stomach acid and is often prescribed for seniors with acid reflux or
            gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD).
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Anti-anxiety Medications (e.g., Lorazepam)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Prescribed to manage anxiety disorders or insomnia in older adults.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Antidepressants (e.g., Sertraline)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Commonly prescribed to seniors for the treatment of depression and mood disorders.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Bisphosphonates (e.g., Alendronate)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Medications to prevent and treat osteoporosis by increasing bone density.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <strong>Anti-inflammatory Medications (e.g., Ibuprofen)</strong>
        <p>
            <strong>Usage:</strong> Prescribed for managing pain and inflammation, but caution is needed due to potential
            side effects, especially in older adults.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>